<p>Farm Bill- House Ag Committee Hearings</p>
<p>Ron Smith reported yesterday at the Southwest Farm Press Online that, &ldquo;Brazil and the World Trade Organization are dealing with a situation that bears little resemblance to real world conditions in the cotton market, Collin Peterson, chairman of the House Ag Committee, said during a farm bill field hearing Monday in Lubbock.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Peterson, commenting on the negotiations currently underway with Brazil to prevent retaliatory measures allowed by the WTO ruling against the U.S. Cotton program, said the issue is based on situations that existed under previous farm bills. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s about past history,&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;Brazil is suing you over past history.&rsquo;&rdquo;<br />
</p>
<p>Yesterday&rsquo;s article added that, &ldquo;[Peterson] also said future trade negotiations that don&rsquo;t include ag will not fly. &lsquo;We will not live with it if agriculture is not (treated fairly). Without agriculture they will not get a deal.&rsquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He quipped that the only way U.S. agriculture could get a fair deal from the WTO was &lsquo;to figure out a way to become a developing nation.&rsquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;He said the next farm bill likely would include changes for cotton because of the WTO/Brazil case. &lsquo;We&rsquo;ll have to do something but I&rsquo;m not certain what. We&rsquo;re not sure what Brazil wants, but we will have to change. My interest is to protect the safety net for production agriculture so that it works for the producer.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>To listen to some comments regarding the WTO Brazil cotton case made by Chairman Peterson at Monday&rsquo;s hearing, click here (MP3-1:01).</p>
<p>Mr. Smith also noted in his article that, &ldquo;Brad Heffington, a cotton producer from Lamb County, Texas, said the WTO/Brazil cotton case complicates discussions about the cotton program. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s a complex program and the case was filed under two previous farm bills. Cotton acreage has decreased by about half since the case was first filed. We don&rsquo;t know what they want.&rsquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;Now, we have a foreign country dictating to our Congress what our laws should be. I don&rsquo;t believe cotton was ever the main issue, but other goods. I&rsquo;m at a loss as to what we should do.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Heffington&rsquo;s comments came in response to a question by Rep. Glenn Thompson (R-Pennsylvania), to listen to a portion of their exchange on this issue from Monday, just click here (MP3-1:32).</p>
<p>Also with respect to the Brazilian cotton case issue, The Wall Street Journal editorial board opined today that, &ldquo;U.S. cotton farmers took in almost $2.3 billion dollars in government subsidies in 2009, and the top 10% of the recipients got 70% of the cash. Now Uncle Sam is getting ready to ask taxpayers to foot the bill for another $147.3 million a year for a new round of cotton payments, this time to Brazilian growers.&rdquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Talk about taxpayer double jeopardy. As Senator Richard Lugar (R., Ind.) said recently, the commodity credit program was established to assist U.S. agriculture, &lsquo;not to pay restitution to foreign farmers who won a trade complaint against a U.S. farm subsidy program.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>The Journal opinion item added that, &ldquo;Mr. Lugar wants the subsidies to U.S. farmers cut by the amount that will have to be sent to Brazil. He adds that a better option would be to take on the trade-distortions of the cotton program&hellip;This is probably tilting at political windmills, since [President] Obama has shown no appetite for trade promotion, much less confronting a cotton lobby supported by such Democrats as Arkansas Senator Blanche Lincoln. But we&rsquo;re glad to see that at least Mr. Lugar is willing to call out the absurdity of U.S. taxpayers subsidizing foreign farmers to satisfy the greed of a few American cotton growers.&rdquo;</p>
<p>In other Farm Bill news, Dave Wilkins reported yesterday at the Capital Press Online that, &ldquo;USDA&rsquo;s Conservation Stewardship Program still appears to be a work in progress.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Since its introduction in 2002, CSP has evolved into a voluntary nationwide program with a competitive application process. Individual farms are ranked based on their existing and proposed conservation practices.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The article added that, &ldquo;The change to a competitive application process from a watershed-to-watershed approach has made the program more accessible to all growers and thus more equitable, Scott Brown, president of the Idaho Grain Producers Association, told the U.S. House Agricultural Committee during a field hearing May 1 in Nampa, Idaho.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Yesterday&rsquo;s article noted that, &ldquo;Given the current federal budget deficit situation, [Fred Brossy, an organic farmer from Shoshone, Idaho] suggested that direct and counter-cyclical payments be tied to CSP qualifiers.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;This would really link food production to conservation stewardship, an appropriate national policy and worthy purpose for a farm bill,&rsquo; Brossy told the committee.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Wilkins indicated that, &ldquo;Chairman Collin Peterson, D-Minn., was cool to the idea.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The primary purpose of federal farm programs is to provide a safety net for producers, and eligibility for direct commodity payments shouldn&rsquo;t be linked to specific conservation practices, Peterson said.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;I&rsquo;m all for conservation, but I&rsquo;m not sure we want to mix that up with what I think the purpose of having a farm program is &hellip; which is to give people the ability to manage their risk,&rsquo; he said.&rdquo;</p>
<p>More broadly on the issue of direct payments and conservation compliance, recall that in an Agri-Pulse &ldquo;Open Mic&rdquo; interview earlier this month (May 3) with Stewart Doan, Rep. Steve King (R-Iowa) suggested that he would try to change the name of &ldquo;direct payments&rdquo; to &ldquo;conservation compliance payments.&rdquo; Rep. King implied that the payments offer an incentive for producers to stay in conservation compliance to avoid the forfeiture of the payments. Rep. King&rsquo;s comments on this issue from the Open Mic interview can be heard here (MP3-0:29).</p>
<p>Rep. King also brought up the issue of direct payments and conservation compliance at the Farm Bill hearing in Des Moines, Iowa on April 30. There, he indicated that the receipt of direct payments was an incentive for producers to maintain conservation compliance; in fact he noted that, &ldquo;conservation compliance would be the purpose of direct payments.&rdquo; To listen to a short portion of Rep. King&rsquo;s comments on this issue from the Iowa field hearing, just click here (MP3-0:32).</p>
<p>The benefits of direct payments to taxpayers are often difficult to explain; highlighting conservation compliance as a prerequisite to maintaining those payments could make it easier for urban voters to see the benefit of direct payments. In some ways, this general concept has been incorporated into the European Union&rsquo;s &ldquo;single farm payment&rdquo; program. As has been articulated under the &ldquo;cross-compliance&rdquo; principle of EU direct payments: &ldquo;To receive direct payments, farmers must meet certain standards concerning public, animal and plant health, the environment and animal welfare and keep their land in good agricultural and environmental condition. Where farmers fail to meet those standards, the direct payments they can claim are reduced or even withdrawn completely for the year concerned.&rdquo;</p>
