<p>Competition</p>
<p><font style="background-color:#E6EEFF">DTN Ag Policy Editor Chris Clayton highlighted several interesting issues regarding the poultry industry and competition in an article from yesterday. The article began with a description of a Tennessee farmer&rsquo;s experience with Tyson Foods that culminated into a legal battle; the article noted that, &ldquo;Poultry producers claim they are a captive class of farmer who can find themselves in debt, empty bird houses and no income if they complain about problems to company management. Producers like [Tom] Terry question whether any changes can come from federal hearings such as the one the Department of Justice and USDA are holding on poultry competition Friday at Alabama A&amp;M University in Huntsville.&rdquo;</font></p>
<p><font style="background-color:#E6EEFF">The DTN article pointed out that, &ldquo;Rising to defend poultry integrators at Friday&rsquo;s hearing, the National Chicken Council released a report Wednesday stating that the industry is competitive and fair. &lsquo;On the national scale, it is the overall conclusion of this study that the chicken industry is a competitive and thriving sector,&rsquo; wrote Thomas Elam, an agricultural economist and president of FarmEcon LLC, who produced the study for NCC. &lsquo;Intense competition among chicken companies leads to product innovation and lower prices for consumers. The vertically integrated structure of the industry has given it an advantage compared to its competitors and allowed it to respond quickly to changing consumer demand.&rsquo;&rdquo;</font></p>
<p>Bloomberg writer Shruti Date Singh reported yesterday that, &ldquo;The [DOJ-USDA] workshop will focus on competition, compensation and regulatory issues in the poultry industry. The event is the second of five sponsored by the departments as part of a broader effort to analyze competition in the agricultural industry.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;Poultry farmers are struggling,&rsquo; Jonathan Buttram, president of the Alabama Contract Poultry Growers Association, said in an interview today. &lsquo;We need some money and contract changes.&rsquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;Buttram said he would like to see processors pay for upgrades and improved contract terms for growers.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Ag Economy</p>
<p>Dan Piller reported yesterday at the Green Field Blog (The Des Moines Register) that, &ldquo;The Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago said today that farmland values rose 8 percent in Iowa from April, 2009 through last month.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The fed based the report on a survey of 215 member bankers in its Iowa, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan and Wisconsin district.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, and the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas also recently released updated reports on agricultural credit conditions and land values.</p>
<p>Steve Jordan reported yesterday at the Omaha World-Herald Online that, &ldquo;A survey of bankers indicated that the rural Midwest&rsquo;s economy is growing for the first time since January 2008.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The Rural Mainstreet Index registered 54.3 on a scale of zero to 100, above the growth-neutral level of 50 after 27 straight months below 50, which indicated economic decline. The index was 44.2 in April.&rdquo;</p>
<p>And Reuters writers Charles Abbott and Christopher Doering reported yesterday that, &ldquo;China bought more than $10 billion of U.S. farm exports in the first six months of the fiscal year to become the country&rsquo;s No. 1 buyer, Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack said on Thursday.</p>
<p>&ldquo;During an interview with Reuters, Vilsack said U.S. farm exports during the first half of fiscal 2010 totaled $59 billion, &lsquo;the best six months ag trade has had.&rsquo; With the strong start, the Agriculture Department probably will raise its forecast of sales for the year, he added.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The forecast now is $100 billion for total U.S. agriculture exports for the fiscal year ending on Sept. 30, up from the recession-hit $98 billion tallied in 2009 and second to the record $115 billion in 2008. USDA will update its export forecast on May 27.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Biofuels</p>
<p>Dan Morgan reported earlier this week at the Fiscal Times that, &ldquo;As the Administration moves closer to a ruling that could put more ethanol made from corn in the gasoline tanks of ordinary cars and trucks, the U.S. automobile industry is urging President Obama to put on the brakes.</p>
<p>&ldquo;At issue is whether to waive current limits set by the Clean Air Act, and raise by 50 percent the amount of ethanol than can be mixed with the gasoline sold at service stations. But a coalition led by auto manufacturers and the oil industry warn that more ethanol in the gas tank could damage engines and lead to more pollution, and they have urged the administration to postpone a decision until next year, pending the outcome of studies.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Morgan noted that, &ldquo;The collision between Detroit and the ethanol industry &mdash; which has strong bipartisan support from the influential farm bloc in Congress &mdash; is rife with political implications. Ethanol refineries from the Dakotas to Ohio are suffering from a glut of supply caused by rapid growth in refining capacity and a downturn in U.S. gasoline use during the recession. The already heavily subsidized industry wants help from Washington on a number of fronts.</p>
<p>&ldquo;With ethanol production on track to reach or exceed 10 percent of the U.S. transportation fuel market this year, the corn belt sees the proposed 50 percent increase in blending limits as crucial to the continued health of the industry and rural economies.</p>
<p>&ldquo;For its part, the Obama administration appears to be hoping that its support for ethanol will partially deflect farm-state criticism of administration proposals to revamp and reduce farm subsidies and enact a climate change law &mdash; initiatives that are unpopular in many rural communities. On an April swing through the Midwest aimed at boosting farm-state Democrats in coming tough congressional races, Obama visited an ethanol plant and said there should be &lsquo;no doubt that renewable homegrown fuels are a key part of our strategy for a clean-energy future.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>Climate Issues</p>
<p>Reuters writer Richard Cowan reported yesterday that, &ldquo;A climate change bill unveiled last week in the U.S. Senate would create hundreds of thousands of jobs as the country moves away from fossil fuels toward more nuclear energy and renewable sources of power, according to a nonpartisan study released on Thursday.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;Between 2011 and 2020, average annual employment in the U.S. increases by 203,000,&rsquo; concluded the study by the Peterson Institute for International Economics.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The study is the first to assess the economic impact of legislation sketched out by Democratic Senator John Kerry and independent Senator Joseph Lieberman.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Robin Bravender of ClimateWire reported yesterday at The New York Times Online that, &ldquo;The Senate will likely vote on a climate change measure in the next few weeks.</p>
<p>&ldquo;But it won&rsquo;t be on comprehensive cap-and-trade legislation. Sen. Lisa Murkowski (R-Alaska) has until the week of June 7 to call for a floor vote on her resolution to handcuff U.S. EPA&rsquo;s forthcoming climate regulations.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Many observers see Murkowski&rsquo;s resolution as doomed, in part because it is unlikely to win President Obama&rsquo;s signature if it clears both chambers of Congress or withstands a veto. But even if it fails, observers say the vote could signal whether the Senate is prepared to quash or kick-start the climate bill from Sens. John Kerry (D-Mass.) and Joe Lieberman (I-Conn.).&rdquo;</p>
<p>The article added that, &ldquo;Sen. James Inhofe (R-Okla.) fears that a failed attempt to block EPA could send the wrong signal.</p>
<p>&ldquo;Inhofe, the top Republican on the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee and leading skeptic of climate science, has said that he is leaning against calling for a vote on the EPA resolution unless victory is assured. Otherwise, he said, the backers of Senate climate legislation would interpret the votes against the resolution as votes for a cap-and-trade bill.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Food Security</p>
<p>Scott Kilman reported in today&rsquo;s Wall Street Journal that, &ldquo;The Obama administration, signaling a shift in U.S. foreign policy in the wake of the 2008 food crisis, said Thursday it wants to spend at least $3.5 billion over the next three years to help potentially 60 poor nations feed themselves.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The initiative, the budget for most of which has yet to be approved by Congress, would be a break from the recent past in which the U.S. has largely helped hungry nations by spending roughly $2 billion annually to donate U.S.-grown food, a strategy that has aided U.S. farmers and shippers.</p>
<p>&ldquo;&lsquo;Agricultural development is a springboard for broader economic development,&rsquo; said Rajiv Shah, administrator of the U.S. Agency for International Development. &lsquo;And food security is the foundation for peace and opportunity.&rsquo;&rdquo;</p>
<p>Mr. Kilman added that, &ldquo;In a report released Thursday on the initiative, which is called Feed the Future, the administration said it initially plans to focus on 12 African countries, four Asian countries and four Latin American and Caribbean countries. The list, which could change, includes Ethiopia, Rwanda, Liberia, Mali, Bangladesh and Haiti.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The countries are required to draw up their own development plans, which could include everything from establishing research stations and breeding better seed to giving farmers access to credit, insurance and markets.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Financial Regulation</p>
<p>Brady Dennis reported in today&rsquo;s Washington Post that, &ldquo;The Senate approved far-reaching new financial rules on Thursday aimed at preventing the risky behavior and regulatory failures that brought the economy to the brink of collapse two years ago and cost millions of Americans their jobs and savings.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The Post article added that, &ldquo;The vote gives Obama his second major legislative victory of the year, following the March passage of his landmark health-care bill. &lsquo;Our goal is not to punish the banks,&rsquo; he said in the White House Rose Garden hours before the final vote, &lsquo;but to protect the larger economy and the American people from the kind of upheavals that we&rsquo;ve seen in the past few years.&rsquo;</p>
<p>&ldquo;The bill now appears headed to a House-Senate conference committee, where a handful of lawmakers will work to resolve differences between the two chambers. House Financial Services Chairman Barney Frank (D-Mass.) said he aims to wrap up that task in short order.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Political Notes- Arkansas Senate Race</p>
<p>McClatchy writer Michael Doyle reported yesterday that, &ldquo;California farmers are going far afield to help re-elect the chair of their favorite Senate committee.</p>
<p>&ldquo;The state&rsquo;s citrus, raisin, almond and peach producers, among others, have been steering thousands of dollars to embattled Democratic Sen. Blanche Lincoln of Arkansas. Lincoln chairs the Senate Agriculture, Nutrition and Forestry Committee, and is fighting for her political life.</p>
<p>&ldquo;But Lincoln&rsquo;s Democratic primary challenger, too, has been tapping California&rsquo;s deep pockets. Consequently, distant Arkansas has become an unlikely arena for a proxy contest between Central Valley farm interests and San Francisco Bay Area liberals.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The article noted that, &ldquo;&lsquo;We need a farm policy that supports family farmers, not corporate agribusiness,&rsquo; Halter declares on his website.</p>
<p>&ldquo;This is Lincoln&rsquo;s first re-election bid since becoming Agriculture Committee chair in September, though she has always served on the panel since joining the Senate in 1999. She has been closely aligned with traditional crop subsidy programs, leading a 2007 fight against efforts to impose tighter limits on individual farm payments.&rdquo;</p>
<p><font style="background-color:#E6EEFF">And Jerry Hagstrom reported earlier this week at DTN (link requires subscription) that, &ldquo;Arkansas&rsquo; agriculture community will support Senate Agriculture Chairman Blanche Lincoln in her Democratic runoff election on June 8, a key Arkansas farm leader said Tuesday night.&rdquo;</font></p>
<p><font style="background-color:#E6EEFF">The DTN article added that, &ldquo;Ben Noble, executive director of the Arkansas Rice Federation, said the Arkansas agriculture establishment is &lsquo;firmly in favor&rsquo; of Lincoln and that rice, cotton, fish and poultry leaders had sent out a letter supporting her last week. Noble also said the agricultural interests had supported Lincoln financially, but found it difficult to compete with the money from other states that flowed to Lt. Gov. Bill Halter.&rdquo;</font></p>
